{
  "action_id": "54",
  "action_title": "Rear and manage populations of solitary bees",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\nSeveral species of solitary bee in the family Megachilidae are reared and managed commercially as pollinators, mostly for the forage crop alfalfa, or fruit trees.\u00a0These species readily nest in drilled wooden blocks, or stacked grooved boards of wood or polystyrene. Parasites and pathogens can be problematic and a number of control methods have been developed. Rearing methods have been investigated for two other species not yet commercially managed and one replicated trial shows that temperature regimes are important to survival. If rearing for conservation purposes is to be attempted, we would recommend a systematic review of these methods.\nThree management trials with megachilids not commercially managed in the USA or Poland, and a review of studies of managed species, found that local populations can increase up to six-fold in one year under management if conditions are good and plentiful floral resources are provided.\nTwo replicated trials have reared solitary bees on artificial diets. One found high larval mortality in Osmia cornuta reared on artificial pollen-based diets, including honey bee-collected pollen. The other found Megachile rotundata could be reared on an artificial diet based on honey bee-collected pollen, but bees reared on synthetic pollen substitutes either died or had low pre-pupal weight."
}

{
  "query": "What factors are known to influence the occupancy and productivity of artificial nest sites provided for solitary bees?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across replicated trials, occupancy of artificial nest sites by solitary bees occurred in most studies, though one trial recorded no use; reported occupancy rates ranged from 1\u201326% of available cavities [47][80]. Placement relative to forage is important: nest sites should be within about 150\u2013600 m of floral resources [47][80]. Nest design and materials influence productivity: reed stems and wooden grooved-board designs produced more bees per nest than several alternatives, whereas plastic-lined holes and plastic or paper tubes were less productive due to parasitism or mould; for Centris analis, cardboard straws in drilled wooden holes were more productive than grooved boards [47][80]. Repeated provision over multiple years increased use, with occupied nests approximately doubling over three years at given sites, and increases in foraging Osmia or local emergence where boxes were provided [47][80]. Parasites and predators reduce productivity, with measured brood losses from parasitism and other mortality in multiple studies; introduced earwigs and non-native bees sometimes occupied boxes [47]. Excluding ants from nest sites increased offspring production in a replicated controlled trial [46]. Under management, populations nesting in drilled blocks or stacked boards can increase markedly when conditions are good and plentiful floral resources are provided, indicating resource availability strongly affects productivity [54]. Species-specific suitability of designs matters: some species or designs (e.g., soil-filled boxes for a mining bee) were not occupied [47].",
